'''Edinburgh Trams''' is a [[tram system]] under construction in [[Edinburgh]], Scotland. The first phase of the project consists of a sixteen-station, {{convert|14|km|mi|adj=on}} link between York Place in [[New Town, Edinburgh|New Town]] and [[Edinburgh Airport]].<ref name="bus-station-facts">{{cite web|url=http://www.edinburgh.gov.uk/news/article/1005/edinburgh_bus_station_to_remain_open_during_tram_works|title=Edinburgh bus station to remain open during tram works|date=14 September 2012|accessdate=17 September 2013|work=News centre|publisher=City of Edinburgh|quote=The tramline will have 16 tram stops along its 14 km route, 12 bridges, one underpass and a state-of-the-art depot and control room}}</ref><ref name="traminfoed">{{cite web |url=http://www.edinburgh.gov.uk/info/20236/about_the_trams/1968/about_the_trams |title=The tram service - About the service and the project |publisher=City of Edinburgh Council |accessdate=17 September 2013 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20130828065327/http://www.edinburgh.gov.uk/info/20236/about_the_trams/1968/about_the_trams |archivedate=28 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/transport/tram-adds-york-place-stop-to-lure-extra-passengers-1-1988261 |title=Tram adds York Place stop to lure extra passengers |work=The Scotsman |date=29 November 2011 |accessdate=10 April 2012}}</ref> Construction has been ongoing since 2008, but has been met with many delays and contractual disputes. Only half of the line proposed at the start of construction is being built. Originally, it was meant to stretch from the airport to [[Newhaven, Edinburgh|Newhaven]], but this was truncated due to a funding crisis.<ref name=u-turn /> Another line serving the [[Southside, Edinburgh|Southside]] has been postponed indefinitely. The system will be operated by ''Edinburgh Trams Limited'', a company owned by the [[City of Edinburgh Council]].<ref name="transdev-cancelled" />
 
The first part of the tram system was originally scheduled to open in February 2011.<ref name="en-20110225">{{cite news |url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/time-s-up-today-s-the-day-the-first-tram-should-have-been-running-in-edinburgh-1-1491901 |title=Time's up: Today's the day the first tram should have been running in Edinburgh |work=The Scotsman |first=Chris |last=Marshall |date= 25 February 2011 |accessdate=20 April 2011}}</ref> By March 2010, project delays had resulted in the prime contractor revising their estimated completion date to 2014,<ref name="bbc-30-months" /> and by the end of 2010 only 28% of the infrastructure had been completed.<ref name="bbc-skills">{{cite news|title=Edinburgh tram firm 'at risk of lacking skills'|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-edinburgh-east-fife-12342581|work=BBC News |accessdate=24 May 2011|date=2 February 2011}}</ref> The whole scheme was originally costed in 2003 at <U+00A3>375 million.<ref name=scotsman-20110513>{{cite news |last=Marshall |first=Chris |title=Tram spend so far hits <U+00A3>440m |url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/tram-spend-so-far-hits-163-440m-1-1630547 |accessdate=16 May 2011 |work=The Scotsman |date=13 May 2011}}</ref> A report issued in August 2011 estimated that the final cost of the truncated network would be over <U+00A3>1 billion, including <U+00A3>228 million of interest payments on a 30-year loan to cover the funding shortfall.<ref name=bbc-loan>{{cite news |title=Council to borrow <U+00A3>231m for Edinburgh trams project |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-edinburgh-east-fife-14594872 |work=BBC News |accessdate=19 August 2011 |date=19 August 2011}}</ref>

{{As of|2013|9}}, work continues on the tram scheme. The system is scheduled to open by May 2014.<ref name=autogenerated3>{{cite news |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-edinburgh-east-fife-24124047 |title=Edinburgh trams: Services 'will be running by next May |work=BBC News |date=17 September 2013 |accessdate=17 September 2013}}</ref>

==History==
Edinburgh's previous tram system, [[Edinburgh Corporation Tramways]], ran from 1871 until it was decommissioned on 16 November 1956.<ref name="tramhist">{{cite web |url=http://www.edinburgh-history.co.uk/edinburgh-trams.html |title=History of Trams in Edinburgh |accessdate=15 September 2013 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20120210083845/http://www.edinburgh-history.co.uk/edinburgh-trams.html |archivedate=10 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=07dnAAAAMAAJ |title=The Edinburgh Encyclopedia |publisher=Mainstream Publishing |last=Mullay |first=Sandy |year=1996 |pages=348-351 |isbn=1851587624}}</ref> Since then, public transport services consisted of [[buses]] and a limited network of [[commuter rail]] lines. Towards the end of the 20th century, there was [[Transport in the United Kingdom#Trams and Light Rail|revived interest]] in trams as a means of public transport, and several British cities such as [[Midland Metro|Birmingham]], [[Manchester Metrolink|Manchester]] and [[Nottingham Express Transit|Nottingham]] introduced new tram schemes.<ref name="scottramrev">{{cite news |url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/scottish-news/tram-system-set-for-scottish-revival-1303636 |title=Tram system set for Scottish revival |work=Daily Record |date=5 September 2012 |accessdate=17 September 2013}}</ref><ref name="tramcostbarrier">{{cite web |url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/trams-hit-cost-barrier-1342433.html |title=Trams hit cost barrier |work=The Independent |date=17 March 1996 |accessdate=17 September 2013}}</ref>

Various proposals for a new Edinburgh tram network were made in the 1990s, and a plan to build a line along [[Princes Street]] and [[Leith Walk]] to [[Newhaven, Edinburgh|Newhaven]] pier was unveiled in 1999 by the City of Edinburgh Council, [[Scottish Enterprise|Lothian and Edinburgh Enterprise]] and the New Edinburgh Tramways Company.<ref name="herald-1999">{{cite news |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/capital-on-track-to-see-return-of-the-trams-1.288289 |title=Capital on track to see return of the trams |date=4 June 1999 |publisher=Glasgow Herald |accessdate=13 January 2010}}</ref><ref name="lrta-u-turn">{{cite web |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20110720111051/http://lrta.info/Facts/facts111.html |archivedate=20 July 2011 |title=Scottish Light Rail : is it a "U" Turn? |publisher=Light Rail Transit Association |url=http://lrta.info/Facts/facts111.html |accessdate=13 January 2010}}</ref>

===Proposals for a new Edinburgh tram network===
{{Main|Proposals for new tram lines in Edinburgh}}
The original 2001 proposal for Edinburgh Trams envisaged three routes across the city, lines 1, 2 and 3; the first being a circular route running around the northern suburbs, while the other two formed radial routes running out to [[Newbridge, Edinburgh|Newbridge]] in the west and to [[Newcraighall]] in the south respectively.<ref name="fact8">{{cite web |url=http://www.edinburghtrams.com/include/uploads/story_so_far/Tram_Factsheets_2.pdf |title=Tram Facts 8 |year=2006 |publisher=City of Edinburgh Council}}{{dead link|date=September 2013}}</ref> All lines would run through the city centre. In May 2004, a 15-year operating contract for Edinburgh Trams was awarded to [[Transdev]], who were to operate and maintain the tram network.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://archive.org/details/Nr110202Trams1 |title=Edinburgh trams Interim report |date=February 2011 |publisher=Auditor General for Scotland |accessdate=18 February 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/french-firm-to-be-axed-in-major-edinburgh-tram-savings-drive-1-775287 |title='French firm to be axed' in major Edinburgh tram savings drive |work=The Scotsman |date=17 September 2009 |accessdate=18 September 2013}}</ref> This contract was later cancelled in 2009.<ref name="transdev-cancelled" />

Following these transport studies, two [[bill (proposed law)|bills]] were submitted to the [[Scottish Parliament]] to reintroduce a tram network to Edinburgh. Both bills were passed in March 2006, and received [[Royal Assent]] in April/May.<ref name="bill1">{{cite web |url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/asp/2006/7/contents |title=Edinburgh Tram (Line One) Act 2006 |date=29 March 2006 |publisher=legislation.gov.uk |accessdate=13 January 2010}}</ref><ref name="bill2">{{cite web |url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/asp/2006/6/contents |title=Edinburgh Tram (Line Two) Act 2006 |date=22 March 2006 |publisher=legislation.gov.uk |accessdate=13 January 2010}}</ref> Only lines 1 and 2 received parliamentary permission, and funding the construction of the entire network was deemed impossible. Line 3, which was meant to be paid for by a proposed Edinburgh [[congestion charge]], was scrapped when that scheme was [[Edinburgh congestion charge|heavily defeated in a referendum]]. For this reason the construction of the remaining two lines was split into four phases:
[[File:Edinburgh tramway map.svg|center|800px|A map of the planned tramway]]
<center>
'''Phase 1a''' would incorporate the construction of an {{convert|11.5|mi|adj=on|disp=flip}} line from [[Newhaven, Edinburgh|Newhaven]] to [[Edinburgh Airport]] via [[Princes Street]], combining parts of lines 1 and 2. <br>
'''Phase 1b''' would involve the construction of a {{convert|3.5|mi|adj=on|disp=flip}} line from [[Haymarket, Edinburgh|Haymarket]] to [[Granton, Edinburgh|Granton Square]] via [[Crewe Toll]],  comprising most of the remainder of line 1.<br>
'''Phase 2''' would link Granton Square and Newhaven together, completing the line 1 loop. <br>
'''Phase 3''' would have the airport line extended to [[Newbridge, Edinburgh|Newbridge]], completing line 2. <br>
</center>


Nevertheless, the future of the tram scheme came under threat in 2007, when the [[Scottish National Party]] (SNP) published its [[manifesto]] for the [[Scottish Parliament general election, 2007|Scottish Parliamentary election]]. In that document, the party made clear its intention to cancel the scheme, along with the [[Edinburgh Airport Rail Link]], in order to save a total of <U+00A3>1.1bn.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.politicsresources.net/area/uk/ass07/man/scot/snp.pdf |title=Manifesto of the Scottish National Party |publisher=Scottish National Party |format=PDF |accessdate=13 September 2013 |page=19}}</ref> In the debate on the government's transport programme, various opposition politicians made statements defending the Edinburgh Trams project. In particular, Labour MSP [[Wendy Alexander]] said ''"The Minister for Transport, Infrastructure and Climate Change claimed that the costs were out of control, but they are not."''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/parliamentarybusiness/28862.aspx?r=4735&i=38754&c=899393&s= |title=Scottish Parliament Wednesday 27 June 2007 |publisher=The Scottish Parliament |accessdate=2 September 2011}}</ref> Following a vote which it lost in the [[Scottish Parliament]], the SNP-led minority [[Scottish Government]] agreed to continue with the line from the Airport to Leith on condition that no more public money would be supplied if the project overran. A report by [[Audit Scotland]], commissioned by the Scottish Government, confirmed that the cost projections were sound.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/edinburgh_and_east/6243158.stm |title=Climbdown after transport defeat |work=BBC News |date=27 June 2007 |accessdate=21 May 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/politics/top-stories/trams-given-green-light-but-it-s-the-end-for-earl-and-delay-for-other-key-projects-1-906839 |title=Trams given green light |work=The Scotsman |date=28 June 2007 |accessdate=21 May 2010 |first=Hamish |last=Macdonell}}</ref> Initial costs for the scheme were estimated at <U+00A3>498 million, with <U+00A3>375 million in funding from the Scottish Government and <U+00A3>45 million from Edinburgh council.<ref name="docherty-shaw">{{cite book |first1=Iain |last1=Docherty |first2=Jon |last2=Shaw |url=http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=r_hUqVaw8qsC&pg=111#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Traffic jam: ten years of 'sustainable' transport in the UK |publisher=The Policy Press |year=2008 |page=111 |isbn=1-84742-072-9}}</ref>

On 25 October 2007, the City of Edinburgh Council gave approval to the Final Business Case. Approval was given by the Council on 22 December 2007 for TIE to sign contracts with [[Construcciones y Auxiliar de Ferrocarriles|CAF]] for the supply of the vehicles and BBS (a consortium of [[Siemens]] and [[Bilfinger Berger]]) for the design, construction and building of the network.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/scotland/top-stories/city-leaders-back-the-final-case-for-trams-1-1238818 |title=City leaders back the final case for trams |work=The Scotsman |date=22 December 2007 |accessdate=21 May 2010}}</ref> Contract negotiations were concluded in April 2008, with construction of the network commencing in June 2008.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/city-chiefs-give-go-ahead-to-163-498m-tram-line-1-1345855 |title=City chiefs give go-ahead to <U+00A3>498m tram line |work=The Scotsman |date= 25 October 2007 |accessdate=21 May 2010}}</ref> Funding problems and political disputes led to scaling back of the original plans. In April 2009, [[Politics of Edinburgh|Edinburgh City Council]] announced the cancellation of Phase 1b of the project, citing problems caused by the [[Financial crisis of 2007<U+2013>2010|global recession]], saving an estimated <U+00A3>75 million.<ref name="1b-cancellation-bbc" /> This decision meant that the construction of the line to Granton would not go ahead for the foreseeable future.<ref name="telegraph-credit-crunch">{{cite news |url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/scotland/3485321/Edinburgh-tram-network-falls-victim-to-credit-crunch.html |title=Edinburgh tram network falls victim to credit crunch |date=19 November 2008 |work=The Daily Telegraph |accessdate=11 January 2010 |first=Simon |last=Johnson}}</ref>

===Tram works: 2008<U+2013>2012===
[[File:Princes Street, Edinburgh - geograph.org.uk - 1587765.jpg|thumb|Tracks being laid on [[Princes Street]] in November 2009]]

Until August 2011, the tram system construction project was overseen by [[Transport Initiatives Edinburgh]] (TIE), a company wholly owned by the [[City of Edinburgh Council]], who were responsible for [[project management|project-managing]] the construction of the tramway.<ref name="chaostram">{{cite web |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/transport/after-eight-years-of-chaos-citys-pound700m-trams-project-is-stopped-in-its-tracks.14848264 |title=After eight years of chaos, city<U+2019>s <U+00A3>700m trams project is stopped in its tracks |work=The Herald |accessdate=15 September 2013 |first=Damien |last=Henderson}}</ref>

Construction commenced in spring 2007, with the draft business case having been accepted by the Scottish Government earlier that year.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/edinburgh_and_east/6458981.stm |title=<U+00A3>60m released for Edinburgh trams |work=BBC News |date=16 March 2007 |accessdate=21 May 2010}}</ref> Initial works centered around the movement of [[Public utility|underground utilities]] in preparation for track-laying. These works followed a plan by System Design Services (SDS), a joint design team led by [[Parsons Brinckerhoff]] and [[Halcrow Group Limited]]).

In May 2008, final contracts to build the tram system were awarded to BSC, a [[consortium]] of [[Bilfinger Berger]], [[Siemens]] and Spanish tram builder [[Construcciones y Auxiliar de Ferrocarriles]] (CAF).<ref>{{cite web |last=Rowson |first=Jessica |url=http://www.nce.co.uk/final-contracts-awarded-for-edinburgh-tram/1346152.article |title=Final contracts awarded for Edinburgh Tram |publisher=New Civil Engineer |date=16 May 2008 |accessdate=21 May 2010}}</ref>

The initial system uses a mix of [[street running]] and segregated off-road track, with conventional tram stop platforms.<ref name="traminfoed" /> Stops are fitted with shelters, ticket machines, lighting and [[CCTV]]. The network will be operated from a depot at [[Gogar]], close to the [[A8 road (Great Britain)|A8]] roundabout, just north of the [[Gyle Centre tram stop|Gyle tram stop]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.barr-construction.co.uk/projects%2Dand%2Dcase%2Dstudies/industrial%2Dbuilding/edinburgh%2Dtramway%2Ddepot/ | title=Edinburgh Tramway Depot | publisher=Barr Construction | date=2011 | accessdate=18 September 2013 | archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20120428185720/http://www.barr-construction.co.uk/projects%2Dand%2Dcase%2Dstudies/industrial%2Dbuilding/edinburgh%2Dtramway%2Ddepot/ | archivedate=28 April 2012}}</ref>

The route of the tram line required the construction of new bridges to cross railway lines at [[Edinburgh Park]] and [[Stenhouse, Edinburgh|Stenhouse]], and a tunnel under the A8 near the Gogar roundabout. Existing bridges at Balgreen, Roseburn, Coltbridge and Craigleith have also been widened, and the Murrayfield Viaduct was adapted for trams to pass under it.<ref name="railway-technology">{{cite web |url=http://www.railway-technology.com/projects/edinburghlightrail/ |title=Edinburgh Tramway, United Kingdom |publisher=railway-technology.com |accessdate=13 January 2010}}</ref> The works to build a tram interchange at Haymarket station involved the demolition of a [[Category A listed|Category C(S) listed building]], the former Caledonian Alehouse on Haymarket Terrace.<ref name="enviro-statement-line1">{{cite web |url=http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/S2_Bills/Edinburgh%20Tram%20(Line%20One)%20Bill/line1-NTS.pdf |title=Edinburgh Tram (Line One) Bill Environmental Statement |publisher=Scottish Parliament |accessdate=14 January 2010}}</ref> 

Some on-street sections of track had been laid into a special foundation with cobbled road surfacing designed to be sympathetic with the existing style of Edinburgh streets. This, however, was removed in many places due to objections from cyclists.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.edinburgh.gov.uk/download/meetings/id/35396/item_12-york_place_edinburgh. |title=Prior Approval 12/00915/PA at York Place - Edinburgh |publisher=City of Edinburgh Council |accessdate=17 September 2013}}</ref> The trams are powered by overhead cables, which are either attached to purposely-built poles or mounted to the sides of buildings.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/opinion/letters/tram-wires-on-buildings-keep-the-clutter-down-1-3040023 |title=Tram wires on buildings keep the clutter down |work=The Scotsman |date=10 August 2013 |accessdate=17 September 2013}}</ref> There were to be nine electrical sub-stations for the line to Newhaven, both underground and above-ground.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/scotland/edinburgh_and_east/7364445.stm |title=Tram work to close Princes Street |work=BBC News |date=24 April 2008 |accessdate=17 September 2013}}</ref> The number of sub-stations was later reduced to five when the line was truncated to York Place.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.edinburghtrams.info/equipment |title=EDINBURGH TRAM INFO |publisher=Edinburgh Trams |date=Q4 2013 |accessdate=17 September 2013}}</ref>

====Project revisions and delays====
During the period between 2008 and 2009, the project was criticised for delays to work on tramway infrastructure, and in particular the closure of [[Princes Street]]. Transport Initiatives Edinburgh underwent some organisational change at this time; in November 2008, Willie Gallagher stepped down as executive chairman of the company.<ref name="journal-gallagher">{{cite news |url=http://www.journal-online.co.uk/article/5108-edinburgh-tram-boss-resigns |title=Edinburgh tram boss resigns |date=23 November 2008 |work=The Journal |accessdate=15 January 2010}}</ref> David Mackay, then Chairman of Transport Edinburgh Limited, took over as interim chairman<ref name="tie-mackay">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/edinburgh_and_east/7735563.stm |title=Interim leader for capital trams |date=18 November 2008 |work=BBC News |accessdate=18 September 2013}}</ref> until he was replaced in May 2009 by Richard Jeffrey.<ref name="jeffrey-ceo">{{cite news |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-edinburgh-east-fife-13454021 |title=Richard Jeffrey quits as Edinburgh tram chief executive |date=19 May 2011 |work=BBC News |accessdate=18 September 2013}}</ref>

In April 2009, Phase 1b of the tram construction project was cancelled due to financial problems.<ref name="1b-cancellation-bbc">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/edinburgh_and_east/8016093.stm |title=Funding concerns for tram project |date=24 April 2009 |work=BBC News |accessdate=11 January 2010}}</ref> Ongoing contractual disputes also delayed track-laying work in the city centre. In December 2009, there were media reports that the project budget was running over <U+00A3>545 million, and that the tram system was likely to come into operation at least seven months late, putting the launch date back to February 2012 or later.<ref name="herald-saga-09">{{cite news |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/blogs/scotland-now/edinburgh-trams-saga-is-far-from-over-1.991682 |title=Edinburgh trams saga is far from over |last=Henderson |first=Damien |date=12 December 2009 |work=The Herald |accessdate=15 January 2010}}</ref> Reports in January 2010 suggested that certain important [[Milestone (project management)|milestones]] of the construction schedule had [[Project slippage|slipped]] by up to two years.<ref name="en-shambolic">{{cite news |url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/scotland/top-stories/shambolic-tram-project-is-up-to-two-years-behind-1-1228943 |title='Shambolic' tram project is up to two years behind |last=Marshall |first=Chris |date=25 January 2010 |work=The Scotsman |accessdate=25 January 2010}}</ref> In March 2010, Bilfinger Berger announced that the construction work would be delayed by a further 30 months, with an estimated completion date in 2014.<ref name="bbc-30-months">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/edinburgh_and_east/8560788.stm |title=Tram project 'could be delayed' |date=10 March 2010 |work=BBC News |accessdate=11 March 2010}}</ref> This estimate was disputed by the Council, which claimed a completion date in 2012 was still feasible.<ref name="stv-2014">{{cite news |url=http://news.stv.tv/east-central/162746-trams-contractor-could-be-axed-over-further-30-month-delay/ |title=Trams firm faces axe as it reveals Edinburgh work may take until 2014 |date=10 March 2010 |publisher=STV |accessdate=11 March 2010}}</ref> The operating contract with Transdev was also cancelled in December 2009, in order to reduce costs; the trams are instead to be operated by Edinburgh Trams Limited,<ref name=companySC451434>{{cite web |url=http://data.companieshouse.gov.uk/doc/company/SC451434 |title=Companies House extract company no SC451434 Edinburgh Trams Limited |publisher=Companies House |accessdate=18 September 2013}}</ref> a company owned by the City of Edinburgh Council.<ref name="transdev-cancelled">{{cite news |url=http://www.transportxtra.com/magazines/new_transit/news/?id=18461 |title=Transdev loses Edinburgh tram contract as council seeks to scale down scheme<U+2019>s costs |date=21 December 2009 |publisher=Transport Xtra |accessdate=15 January 2010}}</ref>

====Contractual disputes====
In February 2009, work on the [[Princes Street]] section of the works was stopped due to contractual disagreements between TIE and the construction BSC consortium. BSC reportedly submitted a late request for an additional <U+00A3>80 million funding which TIE was unable to meet.<ref name="telegraph-bsc">{{cite news |url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/scotland/4736023/512m-Edinburgh-tram-project-in-disarray.html |title=<U+00A3>512m Edinburgh tram project in disarray |date=20 February 2009 |work=The Daily Telegraph |accessdate=11 January 2010 |first=Auslan |last=Cramb}}</ref><ref name="stv-brakes">{{cite news |url=http://news.stv.tv/east-central/78176-business-dispute-slams-brakes-on-edinburgh-trams/ |title=Business dispute slams brakes on Edinburgh trams |work=STV News |date=21 February 2009 |accessdate=11 January 2010}}</ref> Dave Anderson, Edinburgh City Council<U+2019>s Director of City Development, expressed the view in an interview with the BBC's ''[[You and Yours]]'' radio programme, that the contractors' claims were unjustified as they had agreed to fixed-price contracts and to bear the project risks.<ref name="youandyours">{{cite episode
|title=Tram scheme hits hard times |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/youandyours/ram/2009_09_thu_03.ram |series=You and Yours |serieslink=You and Yours |credits=Winifred Robinson |network= BBC |station=Radio 4 |airdate=5 March 2009}}</ref> After negotiations, BSC agreed to commence construction work in March 2009 within the original budget, although ongoing disagreements remained.<ref name="scotsman-tram-row">{{cite news |url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/scotland/top-stories/princes-street-works-to-start-at-last-as-deal-ends-tram-row-1-1195975 |title=Princes Street works to start at last as deal ends tram row |last=McLaughlin |first=Mark |date=21 March 2009 |work=The Scotsman |accessdate=11 January 2010}}</ref> Work recommenced and line construction went ahead. In August 2009, TIE began legal proceedings against the BSC consortium over delays to the project,<ref name="times_0809">{{cite news |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/scotland/article6797192.ece |title=Engineers face legal action over Edinburgh tram delay |date=14 August 2009 |work=The Times |accessdate=13 January 2010 |first=Sadie |last=Gray}}{{subscription required}}</ref> and track-laying works on Leith Walk, Shandwick Place and Haymarket were suspended pending the outcome. At issue were a number of alleged changes to BSC's work specification, including track works on Princes Street and <U+00A3>5 million additional costs on foundation work near Murrayfield Stadium. The BSC consortium also alleged that TIE had not diverted the [[public utility|underground utilities]] in time for track-laying to begin, thus breaching contractual agreements and costing the consortium additional staffing expenditure.<ref name="ft-extra_cost">{{cite news |url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/be940888-1a99-11df-bef7-00144feab49a.html |title=Extra cost of Edinburgh tram line fuels dispute |last=Wright |first=Robert |date=16  February 2010 |work=Financial Times |accessdate=17 February 2010}}{{subscription required}}</ref> In January 2010 the independent arbiter found in favour of TIE on some points, but on most of the disputed issues the arbiter ruled in favour of BSC and awarded the consortium 90% of their additional costs, estimated to be worth up to <U+00A3>80m.<ref name="herald-arbiter">{{cite news |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/transport-environment/council-loses-crucial-trams-dispute-1.999062 |title=Council loses crucial trams dispute |last=Henderson |first=Damien |date=16 January 2010 |work=The Herald |accessdate=16 January 2010}}</ref>

Delays in track laying and depot construction affected tram vehicle testing. By September 2009, the construction work was reported to be nine months behind schedule, and CAF was due to deliver the first newly-built tram vehicles from its factory in Spain. With a key [[dependency (project management)|project dependency]] out of synchronisation, TIE held discussions with [[Transport for London]] about delivering the trams to [[Croydon]] to conduct operational tests on the [[Tramlink]] network.<ref name="croydon1">{{cite news |url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/city-s-first-tram-stop-unveiled-in-croydon-1-1217456 |title=City's first tram stop unveiled.. in Croydon |date=8 September 2009 |work=The Scotsman |accessdate=13 January 2010}}</ref><ref name="croydon2">{{cite news |url=http://www.thisislocallondon.co.uk/news/4587166.Scottish_trams_diverted_to_Croydon/ |title=Scottish trams diverted to Croydon |date=9 September 2009 |work=This is Local London |accessdate=13 January 2010}}</ref> In the end, tram vehicle testing commenced in March 2010 on the [[Test and validation centre, Wegberg-Wildenrath|Siemens test track in Wildenrath]], Germany,<ref name="wildenrath">{{cite AV media |url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cVAytcypXyY |title=Edinburgh Trams being tested in Germany |publisher=Youtube |date=2010}}</ref> and in August 2011, Tramlink ordered new trams from [[Stadler Rail]].<ref name=rgi20110818>{{cite web |url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/nc/news/single-view/view/stadler-wins-london-tramlink-tram-order.html |title=Stadler wins London Tramlink tram order |date=18 August 2011 |publisher=Railway Gazette International}}</ref> The tests included artificially recreating the steep gradients of Leith Walk and using weights to simulate the heavy passenger load expected during a [[Murrayfield Stadium|Murrayfield]] match day.<ref name="shocker">{{cite news |url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/scotland/top-stories/trams-shocker-residents-face-window-washing-ban-over-electrocution-fears-1-1232079 |title=Trams shocker: Residents face window washing ban over electrocution fears |last=Marshall |first=Chris |date=4 March 2010 |work=The Scotsman |accessdate=4 March 2010}}</ref><ref name="bbc-network">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/edinburgh_and_east/8548606.stm |title=Transport chiefs 'want Edinburgh tram network' |date=4 March 2010 |work=BBC News |accessdate=4 March 2010}}</ref>

====Funding crisis====
[[File:Edinburgh trams at Gogar Tram Depot.JPG|thumb|Gogar tram depot in 2012]]
Following further disputes and delays to the project, it was reported in March 2010 that Edinburgh City Council were considering cancelling the contract with Bilfinger Berger.<ref name="stv-2014" /> By June 2010, the cost of the project had risen to <U+00A3>600 million or more.<ref name="herald-no-idea">{{cite news |last=Leask |first=David |title=Tram chiefs admit: we have no idea what final bill will be |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/transport-environment/tram-chiefs-admit-we-have-no-idea-what-final-bill-will-be-1.1035908 |accessdate=19 June 2010 |work=The Herald |date=19 June 2010}}</ref> City Council project managers were reported to be in crisis talks, considering a number of options including: borrowing an extra <U+00A3>55 million to fund the increased costs; phasing the introduction of the tram line, so that trams would initially run only between the airport and Haymarket; and terminating the contract with Bilfinger Berger.<ref name="guardian-18-june-2010">{{cite news |last=Carrell |first=Severin |title=Edinburgh trams project in crisis as sacking of key contractor is considered |url=http://www.theguardian.com/uk/2010/jun/18/edinburgh-trams-project-in-crisis |accessdate=19 June 2010 |work=The Guardian |date=18 June 2010}}</ref> The Council asked TIE to draw up detailed costs for truncating the tram line at four possible termini: [[Haymarket railway station|Haymarket station]], York Place, the foot of [[Leith Walk]] or [[Ocean Terminal, Edinburgh|Ocean Terminal]].<ref name="scotsman-cut-short">{{cite news |last=Ferguson |first=Brian |title=Soaring costs may force Edinburgh tram line to be cut short |url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/soaring-costs-may-force-edinburgh-tram-line-to-be-cut-short-1-813537 |accessdate=19 June 2010 |work=The Scotsman |date=19 June 2010}}</ref>

In May 2011, it was announced that contractors would return to work at priority locations (Haymarket Yards, Gogar roundabout and the depot) while the future of the project was decided. In addition, a 10-month programme of remedial work on Princes Street tracks that had been laid earlier was announced, due to crumbling tarmac.<ref name=scotsman-20110513 /> The same month, Richard Jeffrey resigned as Chief Executive of TIE after two years in the job.<ref name="jeffrey-ceo"/> Shortly after Jeffrey's resignation, four [[non-executive director]]s<ref name=scotsman-neds>{{cite news |last=Marshall |first=Chris  |title=TIE bosses 'quit en masse' as trams shake-up looms|url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/tie-bosses-quit-en-masse-as-trams-shake-up-looms-1-1668408 |accessdate=11 June 2011 |work=The Scotsman |date=31 May 2011}}</ref>  and the communications director<ref name=bbc-haeburn>{{cite news |title=Mandy Haeburn-Little to leave Edinburgh Trams project |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-edinburgh-east-fife-13681271 |work=BBC News |accessdate=11 June 2011 |date=7 June 2011}}</ref> of TIE also resigned. This was followed by the introduction of a voluntary redundancy scheme aimed at halving the headcount of the company.<ref name=scotsman-vr>{{cite news |last=Dalton |first=Alastair |title=Half of staff facing axe at troubled tram firm |url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/half-of-staff-facing-axe-at-troubled-tram-firm-1-1680809 |accessdate=11 June 2011 |work=The Scotsman |date=11 June 2011}}</ref> In August 2011, it was announced that further redundancies would be made following the appointment of international consultancy Turner & Townsend to take over management of the project from TIE.<ref name="tandt">{{cite news |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-edinburgh-east-fife-14573152 |title=Edinburgh trams project to be managed by new firm |work=BBC News |date=18 August 2011 |accessdate=2 September 2011}}</ref> TIE itself was disbanded as a company and the directors were awarded [[severance payment]] totalling <U+00A3>406,635.<ref name=tie-payoff-bbc>{{cite news |title=Edinburgh tram project bosses payments revealed |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-18518319 |accessdate=20 June 2012 |date=20 June 2012}}</ref>

On 30 June 2011, the City of Edinburgh Council voted to continue with the project (albeit only between Edinburgh Airport and St Andrew Square), with costs having risen to an estimated <U+00A3>770m, leaving the Council with a shortfall of more than <U+00A3>200m.<ref name=u-turn /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/exclusive-trams-set-to-stop-at-york-place-1-1245146 |title=Exclusive: Trams set to stop at York Place |work=The Scotsman |date=23 June 2010 |accessdate=17 September 2013}}</ref> The option of scrapping the project was considered, but rejected.<ref name=bbc-vote>{{cite news |title=Edinburgh trams: Councillors vote to continue project |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-edinburgh-east-fife-13959276 |work=BBC News |date=30 June 2011 |accessdate=30 June 2011}}</ref> On 25 August 2011, the Council voted to cut the line further to run only between the airport and [[Haymarket, Edinburgh|Haymarket]], reducing the expected cost to <U+00A3>715m.<ref name=herald-haymarket>{{cite web |title=Running trams to Princes Street <U+00A3>60m cheaper |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/transport-environment/running-trams-to-princes-street-60m-cheaper-1.1120202 |work=The Herald |date=27 August 2011 |accessdate=27 August 2011}}</ref> A week later, after the Scottish Government threatened to withhold <U+00A3>72 million of funding,<ref name=bbc-withhold>{{cite news |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-edinburgh-east-fife-14713476 |title=Ministers withhold Edinburgh trams funding |work=BBC News |date=30 August 2011 |accessdate=20 March 2012}}</ref> they reversed this decision, restoring the terminus at [[St Andrew Square, Edinburgh|St Andrew Square]].<ref name=u-turn>{{cite news |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-edinburgh-east-fife-14751711 |title=Edinburgh trams: Council backs St Andrew Square option |work=BBC News |date=2 September 2011 |accessdate=2 September 2011}}</ref> On 29 November 2011 it was announced that the eastern terminus of the tram line would be at York Place instead of St Andrew Square; the intention had been to build the tracks to a reversing point at York Place (but without a stop for passengers). By extending passenger services from St Andrew Square to an additional stop at York Place this would enable Broughton Street, Picardy Place and the surrounding area to be better served at comparatively little additional cost.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/transport-environment/additional-stop-planned-1.1137112 |title=Additional stop planned |work=The Herald |date=29 November 2011 |accessdate=10 April 2012}}</ref>

The first electric wires were energised in October 2011, above newly laid track within the depot at Gogar. Testing of trams began in December 2011 on the first part of the line to be completed (adjacent to the depot at Gogar, approximately {{convert|500|m}} in length).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-edinburgh-east-fife-15337328 |title=First tram arrives at Gogar depot in Edinburgh |work=BBC News |date=17 October 2011 |accessdate=17 September 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-edinburgh-east-fife-16147559 |accessdate=18 September 2013 |work=BBC News |title=Edinburgh trams on track for test trials at Gogar |date=12 December 2011}}</ref> On 15 December 2011 the depot was officially handed over from the contractors to the City of Edinburgh Council.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.edinburgh.gov.uk/news/article/744/depot_handover_marks_major_milestone_for_edinburgh_trams |title=Depot handover marks major milestone for Edinburgh Trams |publisher=City of Edinburgh Council |date=15 December 2011 |accessdate=17 September 2013 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20130202090537/http://www.edinburgh.gov.uk/news/article/744/depot_handover_marks_major_milestone_for_edinburgh_trams |archivedate=2 February 2013}}</ref>

The first section of the line to be completed was between the depot and Edinburgh Airport, in late 2012. Using this section of line, on 19 December 2012 the first test operation of a tram operating at full speed was made.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.edinburgh.gov.uk/news/article/1103/full_speed_tram_tests_mark_the_end_of_successful_2012 |title=Full speed tram tests mark the end of successful 2012 |publisher=City of Edinburgh Council |date=19 December 2012 |accessdate=17 September 2013 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20130202171320/http://www.edinburgh.gov.uk/news/article/1103/full_speed_tram_tests_mark_the_end_of_successful_2012 |archivedate=2 February 2013}}</ref>

====Criticism of the works====
Ongoing delays in the tram works were criticised by local businesses, who claimed that their income had been adversely affected by long-term road closures in the centre of Edinburgh since 2008,<ref name="bbc-traders">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/edinburgh_and_east/7373659.stm |title=Traders create tram action group |date=29 April 2008 |work=BBC News |accessdate=11 January 2010}}</ref><ref name="en-shandwick">{{cite news |url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/scotland/top-stories/traders-unhappy-as-shandwick-place-to-close-for-18-months-1-1226555 |title=Traders unhappy as Shandwick Place to close for 18 months |date=22 December 2009 |work=The Scotsman |accessdate=16 January 2010}}</ref> and by Edinburgh residents who have voiced dismay over the delays.<ref name="youandyours" /> Construction project delays have also been criticised for causing an obstruction across the city during the 2009 [[Edinburgh International Festival|Edinburgh Festival]] and [[Edinburgh Festival Fringe|Fringe]].<ref name="times_0709">{{cite news |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/scotland/article6729696.ece |title=Tram works turn Edinburgh into 'war zone' |last=McIntosh |first=Lindsay |date=27 July 2009 |work=The Times |accessdate=13 January 2010}}{{subscription required}}</ref> Construction was halted once again in January 2010 due to freezing temperatures.<ref name="en-freeze">{{cite news |url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/scotland/top-stories/big-freeze-puts-tram-works-on-hold-1-1227728 |title=Big freeze puts tram works on hold |date=9 January 2010 |work=The Scotsman |accessdate=16 January 2010}}</ref>

Cycling groups in the city have voiced safety concerns after some cyclists suffered accidents when their bicycle wheels became caught in tracks. They also reported that the road surface around the tracks was crumbling, raising further safety problems. In response, TIE carried out road repairs and Edinburgh Trams agreed to fund special training for local cyclists.<ref name="bbc-cycles">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/edinburgh_and_east/8400094.stm |title=Edinburgh tram lines throw cyclists off track |date=7 December 2009 |work=BBC News |accessdate=11 January 2010}}</ref> Further safety concerns have been raised by residents along the tram routes about the suspension of overhead electric cables from residential buildings, with some property owners refusing to give permission for the cables to be attached.<ref name="shocker" />

On September 2011, Princes Street was closed again to all traffic for around 10 months to allow repairs on the crumbling tarmac around the unused tram lines.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/tram_repair_crews_out_to_fix_botched_roadworks_1_1531045 |title=Tram repair crews out to fix 'botched' roadworks <U+2013> News |work=The Scotsman |date=9 March 2011 |accessdate=20 November 2011}}</ref><ref name="bbc-princes-reclosure">{{cite news |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-edinburgh-east-fife-14958817 |title=Edinburgh tram line repair works get under way |date=17 September 2011 |work=BBC News |accessdate=18 November 2011}}</ref> City centre residents filed a complaint with the [[UNECE]] [[Aarhus Convention Compliance Committee]] in December 2011, arguing that traffic diversions through residential streets during the protracted construction of the tramline has resulted in increased pollution and noise, to the detriment of residents' health. The Council countered that monitoring was ongoing and no sites data breached EU limits.<ref>{{cite news |title=UN to scrutinise Edinburgh tram complaint |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-edinburgh-east-fife-16165656 |work=BBC News |accessdate=15 December 2011 |date=13 December 2011}}</ref> Further road closures in the West End were implemented on 23 March 2012.<ref name="moundreopen">{{cite web |url=http://www.edinburgh.gov.uk/news/article/815/latest_tram_works_due_to_start_as_mound_reopens |title=Latest tram works due to start as Mound reopens |publisher=City of Edinburgh Council |date=1 March 2012 |accessdate=15 September 2013 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20130202090526/http://www.edinburgh.gov.uk/news/article/815/latest_tram_works_due_to_start_as_mound_reopens |archivedate=2 Feb 2013}}</ref> The road between Haymarket and through to Shandwick Place was to be closed for works until July 2013. This closure was extended, and now the road is scheduled to reopen to traffic in October 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/transport/tramworks-shandwick-place-to-reopen-next-month-1-3092004 |title=Shandwick Place to reopen next month |work=The Scotsman |date=13 September 2013 |accessdate=17 September 2013}}</ref>

===2013 to present===
[[File:Edinburgh tramline construction, 2012.JPG|thumb|Ongoing tramline construction at St Andrew Street in September 2012]]
Work since late 2012 continued mostly on schedule, and there was even talk of opening the tram system by Christmas 2013, earlier than the original summer 2014 deadline.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/transport/edinburgh-trams-line-may-be-open-for-christmas-1-2986949 |title=Line may be open for Christmas |work=The Scotsman |date=3 July 2013 |accessdate=17 September 2013}}</ref> However, it was revealed on 31 May 2013 that more than {{convert|150|m}} yards of concrete trackbed would have to be replaced between Shandwick Place and Haymarket, because the concrete was not laid to the correct specifications. Edinburgh Council has insisted that this will not affect the original deadline.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/transport/edinburgh-trams-section-of-track-to-be-ripped-up-1-2950473 |title=Section of track to be ripped up |work=The Scotsman |date=31 May 2013 |accessdate=17 September 2013}}</ref>

Contractors later admitted their error with regard to the concrete, and remedial works began. This has led to further disruption of Shandwick Place and Haymarket, which originally to be free of track works by September 2013.<ref name="concreteblunder">{{cite web |url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/transport/edinburgh-trams-contractors-admit-concrete-blunder-1-3038204 |title=Contractors admit concrete blunder |work=The Scotsman |date=9 August 2013 |accessdate=17 September 2013}}</ref> Michael Apter, chairman of the West End Association, stated that "There was a lot of optimism at Easter [2013] and the back of Easter about trams running as early as autumn. It was only with the discovery of these errors that has kicked that back". He added that the date for completion of the trams hung in the balance. Edinburgh Council has not yet released a revised timeline, but still insists that the remedial works while "taking longer than initially estimated", would "not impact upon the overall timeframe".<ref name="concreteblunder" /> In June 2013, overhead electric wires were installed on the city centre portion of the route. This has been considered the "last major step" in the construction process.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.railstaff.co.uk/2013/06/21/edinburgh-wires-go-up/ |title=Edinburgh wires go up |publisher=RailStaff |date=21 June 2013 |accessdate=17 September 2013}}</ref>

Continuing criticism has been launched at the tram project, even as it has neared completion. The ''[[Edinburgh Evening News]]'' reported in August 2013 that the tram would take eight minutes longer to travel between the airport and city centre than the existing bus service. [[Marco Biagi (politician)|Marco Biagi]], a [[Member of the Scottish Parliament]] for [[Edinburgh Central (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Edinburgh Central]], issued a statement saying "People used to think the tram line was just an overpriced upgrade for the airport bus. Now we all know it<U+2019>s just an overpriced downgrade".<ref name="longerthanbus">{{cite web |url=http://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/news/transport/edinburgh-tram-will-take-longer-than-bus-to-airport-1-3050903 |title=Edinburgh tram will take longer than bus to airport |work=Edinburgh Evening News |date=17 August 2013 |accessdate=17 September 2013}}</ref>

Particular controversy erupted over concessionary travel for the elderly and disabled. Originally, it was planned that concessionary travel, that is the ability of those with a [[Scottish National Entitlement Card]] to travel on public transport free-of-charge, was not going to be offered on the tram system. This was despite the fact that Edinburgh Trams is to be run by Lothian Buses, who are mandated to offer free travel to those with concession cards on all their bus routes.<ref name="autogenerated1">{{cite web |url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/transport/call-to-give-elderly-free-travel-on-city-trams-1-2735967 |title=Call to give elderly free travel on city trams |work=The Scotsman |date=14 January 2013 |accessdate=17 September 2013}}</ref> This revelation quickly caused city leaders to support an ''Edinburgh Evening News'' campaign to ensure that concessionary travel would be offered on the new tram system. City transport convener [[Lesley Hinds]] stated "People in Edinburgh have paid through their council tax and their taxes for the trams to get up and running and it would be wrong for a large proportion of the population not to be allowed to use their concessionary bus pass".<ref name=autogenerated1 />

Despite this, the [[Scottish Government]] refused to pay for concessionary travel for the tram scheme, as it does for all bus routes in Scotland. Talks between the Scottish Government and Edinburgh Council eventually decided that concession cards should be valid for tram travel, but that they should be paid for by the Council instead of the Government.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/transport/free-tram-travel-for-the-elderly-1-2780521 |title=Free tram travel for the elderly |work=The Scotsman |date=8 February 2013 |accessdate=17 September 2013}}</ref> It was revealed on 15 August 2013 that the cards would be valid, and that travel would be paid for by Edinburgh Council. However, only people with cards issued in Edinburgh would be able to use them.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.stv.tv/east-central/236181-passengers-to-use-one-ticket-for-both-edinburgh-trams-and-buses/ |title=Passengers to use one ticket for both Edinburgh trams and buses |work=STV News |date=15 August 2013 |accessdate=17 September 2013}}</ref> This compromise upset many people in [[the Lothians]], who often commute or travel into Edinburgh.<ref name="TicketingSCOTSMANAug13" />
On 12 August 2013, it was reported that the future drivers of the trams were beginning to be trained on the completed section of track between Edinburgh Airport and the Gogar depot.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/scottish-news/edinburghs-delayed-776m-trams-finally-2153240 |title=Edinburgh's delayed <U+00A3>776m trams finally on the move... but only go 500m |work=Daily Record |date=12 August 2013 |accessdate=17 September 2013 |last=Sharp |first=Marie}}</ref> On 15 August 2013, Edinburgh Council announced the creation of [[Transport for Edinburgh]], a new public body to oversee public transport in Edinburgh, including both buses and trams. Lesley Hinds stated: "Our first priority will be integration between bus and tram services and we will have the executive directors of Lothian Buses on the board of the new organisation".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-edinburgh-east-fife-23716810 |title=Transport for Edinburgh: New body to oversee trams and buses |work=BBC News |date=15 August 2013 |accessdate=17 September 2013}}</ref>

Edinburgh Council announced on 17 September 2013 that works on the tram scheme were running two months ahead of schedule, and also that the system would be open by May 2014.<ref name=autogenerated3 /> All tram and road works are due to be completed by 19 October. Testing of the trams on the full length of the route is schedule to begin by December.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/news/transport/edinburgh-trams-on-princes-street-by-christmas-1-3096728 | title=Edinburgh trams on Princes Street by Christmas | publisher=Edinburgh Evening News | date=17 September 2013 | accessdate=17 September 2013}}</ref>

==Rolling stock==
[[File:Trams come to Edinburgh - geograph.org.uk - 1175880.jpg|thumb|Edinburgh residents visit a replica of the proposed trams on [[Princes Street]] in early 2009]]
{{Main|Edinburgh Tram (vehicle)}}

A <U+00A3>40 million contract to build twenty-seven trams, enough to for phases 1a and 1b, was awarded to [[Construcciones y Auxiliar de Ferrocarriles|CAF]]<ref name="40mil">{{cite web |url=http://www.railway-technology.com/projects/edinburghlightrail/ |title=Edinburgh Tramway |publisher=Railway Technology |accessdate=15 September 2013 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20130125205101/http://www.railway-technology.com/projects/edinburghlightrail/ |archivedate=25 January 2013}}</ref> However, as the line was cut back to York Place, only seventeen of the trams would be needed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.railnews.co.uk/news/metro/2011/03/24-surplus-edinburgh-trams-set-to.html |title=Surplus Edinburgh trams set to run in London instead |publisher=Railnews |date=24 March 2011 |accessdate=17 September 2013}}</ref> An unsuccessful attempt was made to lease the extra trams to [[Transport for London]] for use on [[Tramlink]].<ref name="herald-2011">{{cite news |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/transport-environment/edinburgh-s-trams-are-on-track-for-croydon-1.1092784 |title=Edinburgh<U+2019>s trams are on track for <U+2026> Croydon |date=26 March 2011 |accessdate=21 April 2011 |work=The Herald |last=Henderson |first=Damien}}</ref>

The Edinburgh trams, built to meet [[Transport Initiatives Edinburgh|TIE's]] specifications, are be bi-directional, {{convert|42.8|m}} long<ref name="tram-facts">{{cite web |url=https://archive.org/details/LrApplrgTramFactsRebrandedEdinburgh |title=Tram Facts |publisher=Edinburgh Trams |accessdate=12 January 2010}}</ref><ref name="gaurdspec">{{cite web |url=http://www.theguardian.com/edinburgh/2010/jun/23/edinburgh-trams-timeline-facts-tram-latest-transport |title=Edinburgh trams: The story so far |publisher=The Guardian |accessdate=18 September 2013}}</ref> and built with [[low-floor]] [[accessibility|access]] to meet [[Disability Discrimination Act 2005|UK Rail Vehicle Access Regulations]] for disabled people. Passenger capacity will be 332<ref name="caf-performance">{{cite web |url=http://www.caf.net/ingles/productos/proyecto.php?cod=4&id=621&sec=prest |title=Streetcars and light subway trains: Edinburgh Tram <U+2013> performance |publisher=CAF |accessdate=11 January 2010 |archivedate=25 February 2012 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20120225050956/http://www.caf.net/ingles/productos/proyecto.php?cod=4&id=621&sec=prest}}</ref> with 80 seated and 250 standing and the trams will be fitted with [[closed-circuit television|CCTV]].<ref name="caf-performance"/>

TIE specified for the tram vehicles to be able to cope with the steep slopes of Edinburgh streets and offer a suitable visual fit to "compliment the streets the trams will be travelling on."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/edinburgh_and_east/5167948.stm|title=City trams to be 'best in world'|date=11 July 2006|work=BBC News|accessdate=11 January 2010}}</ref>

A full size mockup of the front of the proposed tram was constructed in 2009 and put on display on [[Princes Street]] for the public to view,<ref name="mockup1">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/edinburgh_and_east/7920610.stm |title=Mock tram gets visitors on board |date=3 March 2009 |work=BBC News |accessdate=11 January 2010}}</ref> later moving to [[Constitution Street]] at the foot of Leith Walk in April 2009.<ref name="mockup2">{{cite news |url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/city-s-replica-tram-sets-off-for-a-stint-on-constitution-street-1-1197658 |title=City's replica tram sets off for a stint on Constitution Street |date=7 April 2009 |work=The Scotsman |accessdate=18 September 2013}}</ref>

On 28 April 2010, the first real full-length tram was delivered to Edinburgh, and was put on display (on its rails) at the Princes Street stop at the bottom of [[The Mound]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/scotland/top-stories/all-aboard-for-a-look-at-edinburgh-s-first-tram-1-801767 |title=All aboard for a look at Edinburgh's first tram |work=The Scotsman |date=28 April 2010 |accessdate=18 September 2013}}</ref> It was subsequently moved to open storage in [[Broxburn, West Lothian|Broxburn]].<ref name="en-20101124">{{cite news |title=Tram is carted off to Broxburn because Gogar depot not ready |url=hthttp://www.scotsman.com/news/tram-is-carted-off-to-broxburn-because-gogar-depot-not-ready-1-1313019 |work=The Scotsman |first=Chris |last=Marshall |date=24 November 2010 |accessdate=20 April 2011}}</ref> The final tram was delivered in December 2012.<ref>[http://www.britishtramsonline.co.uk/news/?p=2719 Final tram arrives in Edinburgh]  ''British Trams Online'' 5 January 2013</ref>

===Livery===
To create a visual continuity between the tram fleets and local bus services, Edinburgh trams will have the same livery as that of Lothian Buses. The prototype CAF trams were originally decorated with the "harlequin" design that was introduced on Lothian Buses in the 1990s. Following the announcement of a rebranding of the bus fleet in April 2010, Lothian Buses are reintroducing their traditional [[Rose madder|madder]] and white [[livery]], and the Edinburgh tram fleet will now be painted in a matching colour scheme.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/lowdown-on-new-look-for-lothian-buses-600-strong-fleet-1-798089  |work=The Scotsman |first=Alastair |last=Dalton |title=Lowdown on new look for Lothian Buses' 600 strong fleet |date=31 March 2010 |accessdate=18 September 2013}}</ref>

==Operations, fares and ticketing==
===Route===
The {{convert|14|km|mi|adj=on}} route begins running on-street at York Place, in the city centre.<ref name="bus-station-facts"/><ref name="trammap">{{cite web |url=http://www.onlyinedinburgh.com/the-city/transport/trams/ |title=Edinburgh Trams |publisher=Only in Edinburgh |accessdate=16 September 2013 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20130904040237/http://www.onlyinedinburgh.com/the-city/transport/trams/ |archivedate=4 September 2013}}</ref> It then turns into North St Andrew Street, where it proceeds into [[St Andrew Square, Edinburgh|St Andrew Square]]. From the square, the line heads southeast into [[Princes Street]], and then west along that street toward [[Haymarket, Edinburgh|Haymarket]], via Shandwick Place, Atholl Place, and West Maitland Street.<ref name="Openstreetmap">{{cite web |url=http://www.openstreetmap.org/browse/relation/2632877 | title=Edinburgh Trams Map |publisher=OpenStreetMap |accessdate=16 September 2013}}</ref> At Haymarket, the route heads off-street onto a segregated track that runs parallel to the [[Glasgow to Edinburgh via Falkirk Line|Glasgow to Edinburgh mainline]]. It follows the railway line west for about {{convert|4.2|mi|km|disp=flip}}, until it reaches [[Edinburgh Park railway station]]. At that station, it leaves the railway line on a segregated track and heads north to Gogar Roundabout. From the roundabout, the route heads northwest via [[Ingliston]] Park and Ride to [[Edinburgh Airport]], where the line terminates.<ref name="Openstreetmap" />

