===Fare structure===
Ticketing and fares will be fully integrated with [[Lothian Buses]]. The fare for a single journey on the tram network will be the same as on Lothian Buses, and day tickets and Ridacards will be valid on both the trams and buses.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/transport-chief-prices-single-tram-ticket-at-163-1-25-1-1334966 |title=Transport chief prices single tram ticket at <U+00A3>1.25 |work=The Scotsman |date=17 January 2007 |accessdate=21 May 2010}}</ref> Ticket prices are expected to be the same as [[Lothian Buses]] (<U+00A3>1.50 for an adult single as at September 2013)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://lothianbuses.com/timetables-tickets-maps/fares-and-tickets |title=Fares and tickets |publisher=Lothian Buses |accessdate=18 September 2013}}</ref> when the network opens, with journeys between Edinburgh Airport and the Gogar Depot attracting a supplement, which has yet to be determined.<ref name="TicketingSCOTSMANAug13">{{cite web |url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/transport/anger-at-edinburgh-trams-ticket-plans-1-3048079 |title=Anger at Edinburgh trams ticket plans |work=The Scotsman |accessdate=26 Aug 2013}}</ref>

Free travel will be available to Scottish National Entitlement Cards that have been issued in Edinburgh. Passengers living outside Edinburgh will be expected to pay full fare on the Edinburgh Trams.<ref name="TicketingSCOTSMANAug13" />

===Ticket machines===
[[File:Edinburgh tram 02.jpg|thumb|The first completed Edinburgh tram displayed on [[Princes Street]] in 2010]]
At the request of Lothian Buses, installation of 30 ticket machines at key bus stops began in 2007. These allowed passengers to purchase tickets before boarding their bus reducing dwell times and giving more time to select the right ticket for their journey.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/edinburgh_and_east/6034937.stm |work=BBC News |title=On-street bus ticket machine plan |date=9 October 2006}}</ref> The ticket machines were to have been modified to issue tram tickets once the service began. Due to lack of popularity with users the machines were scrapped in 2011. It is still planned to install similar on-street ticket machines at tram stops before the tram service opens.<ref name="en-tickets">{{cite web |url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/lost-track-ticket-machines-for-trams-to-be-reinstalled-1-1572553 |title=Lost track? Ticket machines for trams to be reinstalled |date=5 April 2011 |first=Chris |last=Marshall |work=The Scotsman |accessdate=21 April 2011}}</ref>

===Staffing===
Fifty-two [[Manual fare collection|ticket inspectors]] have been hired to guard against [[fare dodging]]. This amounts to three inspectors per tram, as there are seventeen trams being prepared for service.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/transport/edinburgh-trams-ticket-inspectors-excessive-1-3050905 |title=Ticket inspectors <U+2018>excessive<U+2019> |work=The Scotsman |date=17 August 2013 |accessdate=17 September 2013}}</ref> Edinburgh Council has said that they are aiming for three-percent fare evasion rate, lower than any other tramway in Britain. Nevertheless, the level of staffing has been criticised by various bodies as being "excessive".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/transport/edinburgh-tram-inspectors-to-police-bad-behaviour-1-3009333 |title=Edinburgh Tram inspectors to police bad behaviour |work=The Scotsman |date=22 July 2013 |accessdate=17 September 2013}}</ref>

Thirty-two tram drivers have been hired and trained by [[Lothian Buses]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/scottish-news/edinburgh-tram-drivers-sit-personality-2029979 |title=Edinburgh tram drivers must pass bizarre personality test to make sure they don't scare off passengers |work=Daily Record |date=6 July 2013 |accessdate=17 September 2013}}</ref>

===Journey times and frequency===
The tram is proposed to operate every seven-and-a-half minutes, with a journey time of approximately 33 minutes from the city centre to the airport.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/edinburgh-trams-infrequent-timetable-fears-1-2944543 |title=Infrequent timetable fears |work=The Scotsman |date=25 May 2013 |accessdate=17 September 2013}}</ref> The service is expected to run from 06:00 until midnight on Monday through Saturday. On Sunday, it is proposed that service will run from 07:00 until midnight.<ref name="tram-facts"/>

